Polish Radom P64 with Custom Kydex IWB Holster from DC Holsters 
of Bellingham, and 2 6-round magazines

The P64 is an all steel DA/SA pistol with a chrome-lined barrel, loaded chamber indicator, 
hammer-drop safety,and firing pin block. The pistol is chambered for the 9X18 Makarov
round and it has functioned flawlessly for me with approximaely 500 rounds fired. 

I have installed Wolf hammer and recoil springs to smooth out the trigger 
and dampen the recoil impulse. DA pull is very heavy at about 16 pounds, however

is very thin making it perfect for concealed carry. The P64 has a bit of a cult 
following and plenty of positive reviews -- take a minute and google it yourself.

Current online prices for the P64 are around $230 (if you can find one) with 
shipping, transfer fees and tax. This brings the total to about $300. I will sell 
mine with installed Wolf springs, 2 magazines and a Kydex
IWB holster custom fit to the P64 for $300. 9X18 ammo readily available online 
and is currently selling for about $14 for 50 rounds. This is a great little pistol -- I'm 
just ready move on to something new.

Since I purchased this pistol with my C&R FFL, I will need to record the transaction
in my log. Local sales only. I'll need to see a Washington driver's license and either a CPL,

title: For Sale/Trade:  Authentic 1847 Dated "Mississippi" Rifle by Robbins, Kendall & Lawrence
postcontent:
This is an original "Mississippi” pattern rifle. This is officially known as the U.S. model 1841 rifle. 
They have the classic brass patchbox, triggerguard, buttplate, and barrel bands made of brass. The manufacture date is 1847 and is shown on the lockplate to accompany the production location of Windsor, Vermont and the maker’s mark of Robbins, Kendall & Lawrence. Robbins & Lawrence only made 10,000 of these Mississippi pattern rifles and only produced them from 1845 until 1848.  
The barrel is in the original .54 caliber bore size. When you look down the barrel you can see the lands and grooves of the rifling.  The ramrod in the channel underneath the barrel is a full-length original one that looks nice with the gun.

title: For Sale:  French MAS 36 and 250 rounds of 7.5 French
postcontent:
The MAS-36 is a short, carbine-style rifle with a two-piece stock and slab-sided receiver. It is chambered for the modern, rimless 7.5x54 French cartridge. The rifle was developed based on French experience in World War I and combines various features of other rifles used, like the British SMLE rifle (rear locking lugs resistant to dirt), the US M1917 Enfield rifle (turned down bolt, peep sight), and the German Mauser (five-round box-magazine), to produce an immensely strong and reliable service rifle.
The MAS-36 carries a 17-inch spike bayonet, reversed in a tube below the barrel. To use the bayonet, a spring plunger was pressed to release the bayonet. It was then free to be pulled out, turned around, and fitted back into its receptacle.
These rifles were in service from 1936–1978 and served in World War II, Algerian War, First Indochina War, Suez Crisis, Vietnam War, and the Cambodian Civil War.  
This rifle is parkerized and the condition is very good.  
Local sale and pickup only.  Thanks for looking!

An AR-15 is comprised of roughly a dozen and a half major components / systems, and it's debatable as to which manufacturer makes the best of each.  After months of research, what's not uncertain is the fact that every single piece of this gun is made from parts of the utmost in quality, reliability, fit and finish.  Below is a list of all the components used in creating this one-of-a-kind weapon.  It is 100% custom-build and has never been fired.

Lower Receiver
•	Lower Receiver:  Mega Arms GTR-3H Billet Lower (Machined from 7075-T6 billet aluminum and black hard anodized)
•	Receiver Extension:  VLTOR A5 Receiver Extension Tube (extruded from 7075-T6 aluminum with 7 length-of-pull stop positions)
•	Buffer:  VLTOR A5H3 6.8 oz. heavy buffer
•	Stock:  Magpul CTR Mil-Spec Carbine Stock with Enhanced Rubber Butt Pad (0.70”)
•	Trigger:  Geissele SSA-E Two-Stage Trigger (3.5 lbs. total pull; 1st Stage – 2.3 lbs.; 2nd Stage – 1.2 lbs.)
•	Safety Selector:  Battle Arms Development Bad-Ass Ambidextrous Safety Selector (standard, short, and crank levers)
•	Anti-Rotation Pins:  KNS Gen ST Non-Rotating Trigger/Hammer Pins (stainless steel, black oxide, torx screws)
•	Sling Plate:  I Kick Hippies SLAP Plate
•	Pistol Grip:  Command Arms UPG16 Modular Pistol Grip (interchangeable finger grooves and palm swells)
Upper Receiver
•	Upper Receiver:  Mega Arms GTR-3H Billet Upper (Machined from 7075-T6 billet aluminum, black hard anodized, M4 feed ramps)
•	Charging Handle:  Mega Arms Mega Grip Charging Handle (black hard anodized, 1.1 oz.)
•	Barrel:  White Oak Armament 16” .223 SDM Barrel (stainless steel, fluted, 1:7 twist, M4 feed ramps, mid-length gas system, 2.10 lbs.)
•	Bolt Carrier Group:  WMD Guns Nickel Boron M16 Carrier Group (158 carpenter steel, case hardened, shot-peened, magnetic particle inspected, full auto capable, 40% more wear resistant than chrome)
•	Extractor Spring:  Tactical Springs Heavy Duty Extractor Spring Upgrade Kit (enhanced power 4-coil extractor spring, mil-spec black extractor insert, mil-spec Viton O-Rings)
•	Rail System:  Daniel Defense AR15 Lite Rail 12” Rifle handguard (machined from 6061-T6 aluminum, type 3 hardcoat anodized, proprietary bolt-up system, 14 oz.)
•	Gas Block:  VLTOR Low Profile Gas Block (set screw mounted, .750 bore, matte black oxide, 1.4 oz.)
•	Gas Tube:  Spikes Tactical Midlength Gas Tube (melonited)
•	Foregrip:  Magpul AFG2 Angled Foregrip
•	Compensator / Flash Suppressor:  Battlecomp 2.0 (made from 17-4PH heat treated stainless steel, compatible with GemTech Halo and AAC Omni suppressors)
•	Miscellaneous:  Spikes Tactical Forward Assist and Ejection Port Door (laser engraved with Molon Labe or Ancient Greek for “Come and Take.”

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P228 9mm TRUE MINT CONDITION
postcontent:
This is truly what they call a mint condition handgun, and is probably the best example of what my prior for sale ads meant when they refer to a lot of my guns and accessories as being "time-capsuled." This gun is almost 20 years old (19 to be exact), and yet looks like it just came from the manufacturer and landed on a Dealers' shelf. It's in pristine condition, with only a very, very, very slight 1/4 inch straight scratch along the exact edge of the slide where it sat in my computer desk, and another tiny pinprick dot (1/16 of an inch) also on the slide edge where it must've contacted the surface of the desk drawer. The gun was shot exactly twice in 19 years, probably the first weekend I bought it, and has sat in my computer desk ever since 1994... This is old school, vintage Sig Sauer P228 where it all began about 20 years ago, with its then adoption by the FBI as a primary duty weapon. It's interesting to see that the design of this gun has been so successful that it has barely been modified in nearly 20 years. Interesting too is the fact I did notice a few years ago they did try once to tinker with a re-design of the P228, but are now back again re-issuing this classic design calling it their M11 variant, but it is essentially this same gun, just with night sights. This gun is to Sigs, what the original 80's era Gen 1 Glocks are to Glocks...Comes with original box and original manual, 2 original 13 round mags. 

That said, though the condition on this is truly mint and it's barely been touched in 19 years, I could see how someone might hesitate spending this amount of money on what is still technically a "used gun" (although probably vintage by now), and so I do have a BRAND NEW HK P2000 SK 9mm with night sights still available, contact me
